		<h1>
            		The last word: Who owns home plate?      </h1>
            <h2>In a new book, two legends of baseball&rsquo;s World Series dissect the duel between batter and pitcher.</h2>
      	    <div class="postDate">posted on October 15, 2009, at 9:36 AM</div>
			
			
				                				
			                    <p>REGGIE JACKSON: When I stepped into the box, I felt the at-bat belonged to me. Everybody else was there for my convenience. The pitcher was there to throw me a ball to hit. The catcher was there to throw it back to him if he didn&rsquo;t give me what I wanted the first time. And the umpire was lucky that he was close enough to watch. <br /><br />Gibson was the same way. That&rsquo;s why people thought he was mean. And that&rsquo;s the attitude you&rsquo;ve got to have. When I hit, I felt I was in control of the home-plate area, and it was important that I felt that way. If I let the pitcher control it, it would give him an advantage.<br /><br />BOB GIBSON: I got a lot of mileage out of looking angry. Sometimes it wasn&rsquo;t intentional&mdash;like when I was squinting in for the signs, and the batters thought I was glowering at them. But the fact is, I was deliberately unfriendly to the opposition. I wouldn&rsquo;t even say hello to hitters on the other teams. I didn&rsquo;t want them knowing me. I didn&rsquo;t want them knowing what I waslike or what I was thinking. It was important to me that I retain an air of mystery. I wanted [batters] wary of me. Uncertain. Intimidated. The Pirates had a young outfielder named Gene Clines who came up to me before a game with a baseball and asked me to sign it. I took the ball and tossed it over my shoulder into left field. <br /><br />JACKSON: There are at least three kinds of advantages that the pitcher and batter contest. There&rsquo;s the physical advantage, the strategic advantage, and also the psychological advantage. I didn&rsquo;t want two out of three. I wanted them all. <br /><br />The pitcher has the ball, and nothing happens until he lets go of it. So, as the batter, I felt I had to fight for any bit of control I could get. I expected the umpire, the catcher, and the pitcher to wait on me. I wanted to get ready on my time. I&rsquo;d call time or pause or do something that wasn&rsquo;t too annoying but at least would get the pitcher off his pace. If I could disrupt his rhythm a little bit, just for a second or two, the advantage swung to me. But I didn&rsquo;t want to create an ire, some kind of anger to make him bear down harder. I didn&rsquo;t want a guy to step back and grit his teeth. Being a jerk about it just doesn&rsquo;t work. There&rsquo;s a fine line between annoying somebody just a little bit and angering him to the point where you may get drilled in the back.<br /><br />GIBSON: Him backing out of there all the time, that is annoying, because I liked to pitch in a hurry. But I never let it annoy me to the point that it distracted me. You don&rsquo;t knock guys down for that kind of stuff. They give you plenty of other reasons to knock them down.<br /><br />JACKSON: It&rsquo;s not just stepping out of the box or slowing things down. It&rsquo;s any little edge you can get. When I went to home plate in a game-tied situation or with a chance to do something and help the ballclub win one, I&rsquo;d try to make eye contact with the pitcher. Now, you didn&rsquo;t do that with Hoot&mdash;that&rsquo;s what a lot of us like to call Gibson, after the old Hollywood cowboy&mdash;or a Mickey Lolich or a Jim Palmer or a Catfish Hunter. You weren&rsquo;t going to stare down those guys. But if a guy was a young player, I would wait to get into the box because I wanted him to look at me. If he wouldn&rsquo;t look at me, I felt I had him beat. If a guy did make eye contact, you could find out if you could intimidate him. Later in my career, when I had the weight of a reputation behind me, I did that a lot.<br /><br />GIBSON: Heck, I couldn&rsquo;t see if a guy was looking at me or not. I had enough trouble trying to see the signs back there. Tell you what I did, though. I used to look in and shake off signs just to mess with the hitters. Did that all the time. [Catcher] Tim McCarver would give me a sign and then give me another one that meant shake me off. The thing was, I didn&rsquo;t have that many pitches to shake off to. So I&rsquo;m out there shaking my head, and the batter&rsquo;s thinking, What the hell?<br /><br />JACKSON: Everybody in the league knew I had trouble with the inside pitch. I got away with it only because the great majority of pitchers were afraid of making a mistake in that spot. The threat of power is one of the best weapons you have in the batter&rsquo;s box. They were also concerned that if they missed inside, they&rsquo;d hit me, put me on base. Now, for a guy like Gibson, that was okay. His attitude was, if I&rsquo;m gonna miss, I&rsquo;m gonna miss at you.<br /><br />GIBSON: What pitchers are really afraid of is their own control. They don&rsquo;t truly believe that they can get a pitch in there exactly where they want it&mdash;especially against a hitter as powerful as Reggie, who can put his team on the board at any moment. They know that if they miss in the wrong place, a power hitter will knock the crap out of it. But you can&rsquo;t go out there with the attitude that you&rsquo;re going to miss your spot. You can&rsquo;t go out there afraid of the hitter or afraid of yourself. <br /><br />Contrary to what people thought, I didn&rsquo;t make my living on the inside corner. My idea was to pitch away, pitch away, pitch away, come in, pitch away. I mostly worked the outside part of the plate; but you can&rsquo;t be scared to come in when the time or the hitter calls for it. The thing is, if I&rsquo;m pitching a guy inside, I&rsquo;m going to make sure I get it <em>way</em> in there. If you put the ball in the strike zone inside&mdash;especially against a guy who can hit the ball out of the ballpark&mdash;that&rsquo;s horrible. Left-handed or right-handed batter, it doesn&rsquo;t matter. Don&rsquo;t do that.<br /><br />JACKSON: As a hitter, what I had to learn, mostly, was what I could do and what I couldn&rsquo;t do. A good pitcher might have an advantage with a big fastball or breaking ball, but I had an advantage, too&mdash;a major advantage: I could hit a fly ball and get it out of the ballpark. If I could get the barrel on the baseball, I could put us on the scoreboard.<br /><br />It took a while, but eventually I came to realize that there was something else in my favor: My weakness&mdash;my inability to handle the ball inside&mdash;was one that most pitchers were reluctant or afraid to expose. It would have been a different story if I hadn&rsquo;t been a home-run hitter; but my power was the reason a lot of pitchers wouldn&rsquo;t throw me inside.<br /><br />Hoot may say he didn&rsquo;t like to pitch inside too much, but you can bet he would have buried the ball in on me. He&rsquo;d have shown me the ball away to make me think something might be there, then he&rsquo;d have thrown it as hard as he could inside.<br /><br />GIBSON: I threw my slider a couple different ways. I had a quicker one that got right in on your belt buckle. That&rsquo;s what I would have shown him. That&rsquo;s what I did with [Willie] McCovey when I showed him a slider. Most of the good hitters like that&mdash;those big, strong lefties&mdash;I&rsquo;d work pretty much the same. Try not to give them anything down and in on the plate.<br /><br />JACKSON: One of Ted Williams&rsquo; principles of hitting was that an average hitter swinging at a good pitch to hit is better than a great hitter swinging at a bad pitch to hit. I go along with that. And I honestly felt that when I went to home plate, 85 percent to 90 percent of the time I was going to get a ball to put in play hard. Even facing a guy like Gibson, or any of the great ones. It may not be exactly what you want, and it may be tougher to handle than you hoped for, but you&rsquo;re going to get something hittable.<br /><br />GIBSON: Even the good pitchers make bad pitches, and plenty of them. I couldn&rsquo;t count how many bad pitches I&rsquo;d make in the course of a game. I&rsquo;d guess maybe 20, 25 a game. Some you get away with, some you don&rsquo;t. It depends on who you&rsquo;re missing to. Most of the time good hitters don&rsquo;t miss bad pitches. Other guys go, &ldquo;Damn it!&rdquo; and foul it back. These good hitters go Whack! And they&rsquo;ve got you saying &ldquo;Damn it!&rdquo; Guys like [Willie] Mays don&rsquo;t make mistakes. On the whole, Mays didn&rsquo;t hurt me as much as [Hank] Aaron, and I found him easier to pitch to, but Willie was an example of a guy who just did not miss a mistake. If you threw him a breaking ball and missed it, home run. Willie didn&rsquo;t hit singles off hanging breaking balls. <br /><br />JACKSON: When I was facing a great pitcher late in a ballgame, and the ballgame was close, I&rsquo;d try to get really focused on doing what I do best. That&rsquo;s when it&rsquo;s fun, because the great pitcher is doing the same thing. If it&rsquo;s the eighth or ninth inning, with the game on the line, and Gibson can throw me three strikes on the inside part of the plate, I&rsquo;m going to be an out. I would settle for that, because at that point in the game I&rsquo;m holding out for something away. And I&rsquo;m pretty sure Gibson&rsquo;s going to give it to me, because that&rsquo;s his strength, too. In that situation, we both want to go strength against strength. That&rsquo;s the time to bet on what I&rsquo;m capable of doing, not try to handle something in my weakness.</p><p>GIBSON: There&rsquo;s a pretty good chance you might get what you&rsquo;re looking for, too. Say, for instance, I&rsquo;m working him all night with sliders in. That&rsquo;s [been] my plan. Well, when we get to that moment of truth in the eighth or ninth inning, [if] I&rsquo;ve got nowhere to put him [because the bases are full], I might say the hell with that. There&rsquo;s a decent chance that, since I&rsquo;ve pitched him inside all night, he might not be looking away. On the other hand, there&rsquo;s also the risk that he&rsquo;s given up on the inside pitch by this time and he&rsquo;s holding out for something on the outside part of the plate that he can get the barrel on, since that&rsquo;s his strength. I&rsquo;m well aware of that risk, believe me. But at that point, I don&rsquo;t care anymore. I&rsquo;ve gotten myself into a spot where I can&rsquo;t afford to care. I need a strike so badly that I might just go ahead and throw the ball out there where I know he can crush it if I make a mistake. The thing I&rsquo;ve got going for me is confidence that I&rsquo;m not going to make a mistake. When push comes to shove, you have to do what you do best.<br /><br />JACKSON: I would have one advantage against Hoot. His strength is away, he&rsquo;s confident away, and I want the ball away. I&rsquo;m on the defensive when it&rsquo;s 0-and-2, 1-and-2, but if the count gets turned around and there&rsquo;s no place to put me and it&rsquo;s all there out on the line, I&rsquo;m going to get what he does best. We both know that. Sooner or later, it&rsquo;s going to be me against him, his strength against mine. Now I feel like, come on, let&rsquo;s go.<br /><br />GIBSON: Yep. Here it comes, ready or not. And it&rsquo;s coming out over the plate, just like he likes it. I have no choice but to throw a strike, I can&rsquo;t be that concerned with location, other than just getting it over. I&rsquo;m just going to throw it down the middle, above the belt, with the best stuff I have. When my back is the wall, it&rsquo;s on.<br /><br />Here it is, buddy.<br /><br />From the book <em>Sixty Feet, Six Inches</em> by Bob Gibson and Reggie Jackson. &copy;2009 by Robert Gibson and Reginald Martinez Jackson. Published by arrangement with Doubleday, an imprint of the Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group, a division of Random House, Inc.</p>  	

